There has never been much to my life. There probably never will be. I try not to fill it with a lot of unnecessary stuff. Every few years, something really big changes the shape and texture of my life so I feel like someone entirely new, but at the core, this is basically me.

The day is lazy. If I were back in school, spring fever would definitely have hit. As it is, though, I'm filled with energy. Everything I'd put off, suddenly I do at once. Spring cleaning. For the rest of it, I spend the day reading.

I'm boymoding again outside. I always do here. The people here know me as a guy and I don't want to risk trouble. But it's still nice. I don't really get out enough, but spring promises some time outside, and I'm looking forward to it.

The weather is comfortable today, and we went for a walk. We don't go far, just to the end of the block, but the air feels nice. There's a mockingbird we met years ago and she's come back, so we talk a little about how glad we are to hear her again.

I just wanna say that there's a life out there outside of college and nobody should feel bad for struggling! it has NOTHING to do with how capable or smart you are! It's not a structure conducive to learning!

Two things! 

One: if you don't go or succeed in college, you're not a failure - college is structured in a very specific way to teach you to be a part of a specific management class. 

Two: it shouldn't be required for maybe 90% of jobs and can EASILY be replaced with training.

Which is a long winded way of saying that we treat college as a place to go to get job skills - an investment - and it usually simply doesn't pay out. So all that happens is you grow as a person but then you're chained to debt for the rest of your life. But people require it.

I don't wanna say that my college degree was USELESS because it actually wasn't. I don't think of all the stuff I know, it forms a foundation for other stuff I learn, deconstruct, and build for myself later. I AM saying that I'm not employing it "productively."
I'm almost 40 and still paying it off. I worked jobs, exactly 0 of them required that education except for teaching, but all of them either required or leaned towards the degree.

grad school was great for me in some ways and really really bad in others but I cannot stress enough how much my regular high school and bachelor's college education has not really come into play in my life.

stories and poetry and art are prior to and required for many of the things we think of as necessary structures from states to logistics to ideology to reports to games and so on.

poetry is a refined version of some of this - something we created rules and structure for and then, in a delicate twist of legerdemain, removed the rules from, but retained some of the pretensions that it was above and different from communication. it isn't.

one of the things you can't remove, though, is a product of how we understand our environment, which is "narrative" and this is essentially communication - internal, how we talk to ourselves and external, how we communicate to others. or, anyhow, "art"

and when you look at this, you say "oh no, this thing or that thing, that's needed, we need that. this is about accessibility, that is about quality of life" well, yes, that's true. and would you know what? you'd be right. yeah, these things are about living your life well.

visiting people far from you, talking to people around the world, variety in food, all decoration, temperature control outside of the environment necessary for survival, comfort and softness, social lives, sex and physical pleasure, all "luxury"

the majority of the things that we do in our society are what you would call "luxury" because they're not mandatory for existence. that's something we really need to sit with - because what we consider "life" is largely a construction. strip it away, there's very little left.
one of the major problems I foresee with a post-capitalist society, something that we will require time in order to fully de-program, is that we view labor as prior to and detached from life.

Multiple policies and plans from different groups will be instituted in overlapping areas simultaneously - we can be sure that this will happen because it's happening right now. Revolutions aren't distinct periods but intensification of certain already existing trends.

This will happen asynchronously, they'll spread out like waves from places where they occur to places that hear about it in real time and then delayed via media outlets as consensus is reached about what is occurring, where that consensus is delayed by noise to signal ratio.

There won't be "a" revolution, there will be a series of conflicts both with and without names that will be connected and disconnected from each other that will involve various groups who can't decide if they're on the same side.

It's interesting that people talk about what something is going to be "after the revolutions" because it assumes there will be a discernible revolution you can point to a beginning or an end of, that it will start and end everywhere at the same time, and that there's one answer.

But our society is its own rationale - once established it needs to be perpetuated. Whatever else we do is in service to the ethos of building and all the things that construction requires, over time.

While, in actuality, if you were to play Minecraft based entirely off what you needed only, you'd have a small house and some crops, and nothing else is actually required. I think about that for us, too. We do need things, obviously, and want things. But why?

Here, there's no questions about utility because the eventual drive is to make this genuinely titanic in scope - and that takes a lot of time. But that also means that the building possesses a logic of its own, and everything else is in service to that.

Something I'm thinking about - naturally, construction ruins the view. That's what happens when you build a megastructure. I think "what's the best way to build this? Is it possible to match the environment?" But whatever you build, you alter the landscape completely. https://t.co/eIbi6uqD2E

Solo play is expected (in 11, I progressed at a crawl because of social anxiety. I performed fine but it's hard for me to play with new people every time.)

I don't intend to compare 14 to 11 in terms of whether I like it more or less, it's a different game. You can see how, late into 11's life (and it's still going, you can log in right now), they instituted changes that 14 would complete the logical progression for later.

I'm not gonna lie, really, I appreciated the slower pace although I'm sure I'll get used to this. The oldest areas of the game are extremely dated, 14 is vibrant right off the bat. 11 was designed to play on the PS2 and that was the norm in Japan for a while, I think.

Combat is slower in 11. You can *literally* feel the seconds pass in how long a spell will take, how long the refresh on it is, you'll have timers up but eventually you wouldn't need them. No timers for chains, no timers for most things.

11 doesn't show you where the enemy's attack is gonna land, healing takes much, much longer (much of partying is minimizing downtime), partying was initially required and they built in complex workarounds to that to make it more solo-friendly.

I played a little FF14 today and as someone who jumped from 11 to 14, it's interesting to see how, like, frenetic the pace is compared to 11 (which would probably feel like playing in molasses to 14 players.) 11 is, simply, much less forgiving.

I worked there. I worked at a retirement home as the night guard. I worked as a call center operator in a building alone in a field, I bought my groceries alone, I walked through the empty suburbs and bus stations and terminals alone. It was fine, just lonely.

I don't know. People meme about the back rooms, but maybe they don't understand that it's easy to live there. Every room is just like that when there's nobody there. That's what it's like. I was in there for years. That's how it felt. Not hostile, not creepy, just empty.

Wherever you go, everything seems two dimensional. You can trace the infrastructure with your fingers through the air, see how everything connects to everything else, but you don't have a part in it. People don't even see you until you order a coffee, you sit down for a moment.

Everywhere, there are people going somewhere, doing something, and you're just... there. Nothing makes any sense. Why is everyone doing all this? Nothing relates to anything else. You need money and a place to stay. Nothing else means anything.

A lot of times when you break away from a bad situation, you don't do it at the right time, you do it at the only time and when you do, there's nobody waiting for you and there's nowhere to go, and there's nothing to do and the world is big and open and cluttered and empty.

Or, I don't know, it turns out most of the book is about cooking stuff at home or eating with friends. I just wanted a book that described how I felt in a world that was both normal and collapsing, technically the future but really everything is the same, just... moreso.

I wasn't running from anything, I had just grown up feral and badly, and didn't know where I was or who was around, or how to make friends, or anything, actually. Despite that, I felt there was something to live for. I guess that's what made it into the book.

I had a few friends, but I spent most of my time alone. Maybe two years, moving from place to place like a ghost. I made friends with some crows and played Magic on the weekends, and the rest of the time I read stuff from the half price shop and drank a lot, but less than before.

Later on I found myself in Washington state, sleeping on my friend's floor. That was better. Hard to explain what happened, it felt like some light got let in. I thought I'd probably survive after all. I spent more time alone, and more time later, and more time again.
No hate for the reflection. It can't help what it is. But it's a very bad conversationalist if you're lucky, you know? It's much worse if it's a good one. Anyhow.

When I got out of undergrad, I came back home and there was nothing left. My brother was in jail, my mom had bailed, my dad was working for a little more than minimum wage. I don't remember that period well. Just how it felt. I worked a night shift, I couldn't ever sleep.

It didn't matter if it was good. I had never finished a novel that I'd started. Instead I said I'd write something bad. If it was okay, then great, but the point was to write the whole thing out, so that's what I did. Some of it is pretty good. Maybe a lot of it.
